Part I - Ford GoBike Dataset Exploration Analysis

by Anas Almudayd

Introduction

The dataset, 2019-fordgobike-tripdata.csv, is downloaded from Udacity and licensed by Ford GoBike. This dataset includes 183,412 trips with 16 features such as duration_sec (time of take the bike in seconds), start_time and end, and type of user and its gender, there are also id for the bike, stations, and finally wethear the bike shared durnig the trip or not .

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset includes 183,412 trips with 16 features as follows:

(Column) (Non-Null Count) (Datatype)

  • duration_sec 183412 non-null int64
  • start_time 183412 non-null object
  • end_time 183412 non-null object
  • start_station_id 183215 non-null float64
  • start_station_name 183215 non-null object
  • start_station_latitude 183412 non-null float64
  • start_station_longitude 183412 non-null float64
  • end_station_id 183215 non-null float64
  • end_station_name 183215 non-null object
  • end_station_latitude 183412 non-null float64
  • end_station_longitude 183412 non-null float64
  • bike_id 183412 non-null int64
  • user_type 183412 non-null object
  • member_birth_year 175147 non-null float64
  • member_gender 175147 non-null object
  • bike_share_for_all_trip 183412 non-null object

For Data Wrangleing Process:

  • The null velue have been removed
  • The start_time & end_time have been converted into datetime, they were 'object' as we see above
  • The start_time & end_time have been splited into date_start, time_start, date_end, and time_end to make the structre better
  • The start_time & end_time columns have been revomed after perform the split step
  • The columns start_station_longitude and end_station_longitude values converted into + values, they were all - values! for no reason!!

Now the dataset till here is fully cleaned

plt.xlabel('The generation')

# Now here, in y-axis the numbers looks not well for example: 20000, and 40000
# and while they all more than 20K, it better to make them ends with K like this 20K insted of 20000
# I did some search for the best way to apply it, and it turns out that their is a library needs to be import
# Which is ticker from matplotlib, and we need to make function that convert the regular numbers and make it ends with K
# As I did below
import matplotlib.ticker as mtick # Import this library
def thousands_formatter(x, pos): # Here the function that need to make to convert as I searched
    if x == 0:
        return '0' # Here keep the 0 as is without adding K
    else:
        return f'{int(x / 1000)}K' # And here if the number from the thousands will be converted
# And now its time to use the library that imported to apply the function above
plt.gca().yaxis.set_major_formatter(mtick.FuncFormatter(thousands_formatter))

Still the plot is not well so we need to make it more profional!

Question: Usually, Which is the highest path for (start to take and submit) the bike?

In[44]:
# I will create heat map due to the available data that helps in making it
# Lets divide the work into steps to take a good understanding!
# For FYI I took the 1,2 & 3 from searching due to the size of the data which is too large

# Step 1: Count trips for each station
top_n = 10  # Set the number of top stations to keep
top_start_stations = df['start_station_name'].value_counts().nlargest(top_n).index
top_end_stations = df['end_station_name'].value_counts().nlargest(top_n).index

# Step 2: Filter the df to only include top stations
filtered_df = df[df['start_station_name'].isin(top_start_stations) & 
                  df['end_station_name'].isin(top_end_stations)]

# Step 3: Prepare the data - create a pivot table
heatmap_data = filtered_df.pivot_table(index='start_station_name', 
                                        columns='end_station_name', 
                                        values='duration_sec',  # You can use duration_sec
                                        aggfunc='count',  # Count the number of trips
                                        fill_value=0)  # Fill missing values with 0 if there any

# Step 4: Now let come to the desired point, creating the heat map!
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8)) # Lets set the size to the best possible for looking the plot
sns.heatmap(heatmap_data, cmap='YlGnBu', annot=True, fmt='g')  # Set annot to true to see counts, cmap to YlGnBu to make the color good for looking
plt.title('Top stations who receives the trips')
plt.xlabel('End Station')
plt.ylabel('Start Station')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')  # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
plt.show()
# It will show one important encoding whcui is the colorbar! it will help to differantiate bwteen heats

As we see it turns out the hiest people used the following path to start and finish their trip! starting from Berry St at 4th St, and submit their bike in San Francisco Ferry Building (Harry Bridges Plaza)

In[45]:
# The facet plots will be created and it will show Trip Duration vs Starting Latitude by User Type and Gender

# First for better encodings the starting latitude will be normalized to use it starting from 0 with relative frequency
# Normalize starting latitude
df['normalized_start_latitude'] = df['start_station_latitude'] - df['start_station_latitude'].min()

# Lets create a Facet Plot for trip duration vs starting latitude by user type and gender 
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10)); # The size as usual
facet = sns.FacetGrid(df, col='user_type', row='member_gender', height=4, aspect=1.5) # Here creating the plot, the height and aspect about the layout in the front
facet.map(sns.scatterplot, 'duration_sec', 'normalized_start_latitude', alpha=0.6, color='blue') # The facets will be scatters based on the data that I have
facet.set_axis_labels('Trip Duration (seconds)', 'Starting Latitude') # Here to set the label for the x and y axises
facet.set_titles(col_template='{col_name}', row_template='{row_name} Users') # Here to set the label for the column and rwos of the facets
plt.suptitle('Trip Duration vs Starting Latitude by User Type and Gender', y=1.05)
facet.fig.set_size_inches(14,5)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show(); # In each row there are 2 columns and in each column there are 3 rows, for me this is better!

# From above I googled them to get the optimal ways to draw the facets

# And now we reach to the final plot which matrix plot that will repreasent each one of the numaric cols with the user type!
# Its very interested to see the
# Selecting numerical columns for the plot matrix(pair plot)
# Normalize longitude and latitude to start from 0 and then will be relative frequency for better organizing
df['normalized_start_latitude'] = df['start_station_latitude'] - df['start_station_latitude'].min()
df['normalized_start_longitude'] = df['start_station_longitude'] - df['start_station_longitude'].min()
df['normalized_end_latitude'] = df['end_station_latitude'] - df['end_station_latitude'].min()
df['normalized_end_longitude'] = df['end_station_longitude'] - df['end_station_longitude'].min()

# Select relevant columns for the pairplot with normalized values as you see
numerical_cols_normalized = [
    'duration_sec', 
    'normalized_start_latitude', 
    'normalized_start_longitude', 
    'normalized_end_latitude', 
    'normalized_end_longitude'
]
 
# The above process I need a little search to get them well as I want    
    
# Now its time to the BIG SHOW, create a pairplot with hue set to user_type (the legend will appear in the right)
# When they match two col like duration_sec vs duration_sec will repreasented as line chart, otherwise it will be scatter
sns.pairplot(df[numerical_cols_normalized + ['user_type']], hue='user_type')
plt.suptitle('Trip Data', y=1.02)

The pair plot shows that customers tend to have longer trip durations, while subscribers typically take shorter!

Conclusions

In this Ford GoBike Dataset Exploration Analysis

  • This dataset downloaded from Udacity and licensed by Ford GoBike.
  • It includes 183,412 trips with 16 features
For Data Wrangleing Process:
  • The null velue have been removed
  • The start_time & end_time have been converted into datetime, they were 'object' as we see above
  • The start_time & end_time have been splited into date_start, time_start, date_end, and time_end to make the structre better
  • The start_time & end_time columns have been revomed after perform the split step
  • The columns start_station_longitude and end_station_longitude values converted into + values

For Univariate analysis:

  • I did the histogram, and bar chart
  • for the histogram I asked, Which is the peak that most of the customer use the bike in second? and what kind of the distrubition? and to answer that I had to create the plot and it turns out that, as it clear that the histogram is RIGHT SKEWED distribution, the plots clarify that the most of the users their peak of using the bike is between 300 to 350 seconds approximatly
  • for th bar chart I asked about the top 10 stations that have trips? and two of them were Market St at 10th St, and San Francisco Caltrain Station 2 (Townsend St at 4th St)

For Bivariate analysis:

  • I did the scatter, box plots, and the heat map
  • for the scatter, I asked based on the user age, Which is the generation that used the bike most? they were bewteen 1950s and 2000s
  • for the box, Which the users whose used the bike long time? Particapiate or not? they are who NOT participate
  • for the heat map, Usually, Which is the highest path for (start to take and submit) the bike? and they starting from Berry St at 4th St, and submit their bike in San Francisco Ferry Building (Harry Bridges Plaza)

For Multivariate analysis:

  • I did facet plot and pair plot(matrix plot)
  • for the facet, Who is the highest propotion in the latitude, the answer based on the plot is The male users who subscribe in the program seems to be the highest proption of the latitude
  • for the matrix, How do user types (Customers vs Subscribers) differ in their trip duration, starting latitude, and starting longitude based on the pair plot? and it shows that customers tend to have longer trip durations, while subscribers typically take shorter!

Finally, This exploration analysis was fantastic and enjoyable!
